{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"89d8e168-5df0-4c0f-a145-513b90eacfe6","content":"## Analysis\n\nThe report confirms the overhead is **MSBuild process startup + project re-evaluation**, not compilation. Visual Studio avoids this by keeping a long-lived MSBuild host in memory. Here are three CLI-side fixes, ranked by impact:\n\n### 1. Use `dotnet watch` for the inner loop (biggest win)\nKeeps the build host alive and rebuilds on file changes — no process startup per build:\n```bash\ndotnet watch build\n```\n\n### 2. Enable the MSBuild Server (SDK 8.0.3xx+)\nA long-lived MSBuild server node (similar to how VS works) that persists between `dotnet build` invocations:\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\ndotnet build          # first run warms the server\ndotnet build          # subsequent runs reuse it — much faster\n```\nYou can set this permanently in a shell profile or in a `Directory.Build.rsp` file at the repo root:\n```\n-nodeReuse:true\n```\n\n### 3. Add `<BuildInParallel>` and graph builds for multi-project solutions\nNot needed for this single project, but for larger repos:\n```bash\ndotnet build --graph   # evaluates the project graph once\n```\n\n### Recommendation\nFor quick edit-build-test cycles on this project, **`dotnet watch build`** is the simplest, most effective change — it eliminates the per-invocation startup entirely and mirrors the always-warm experience Visual Studio provides.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0d4cd1d2-cddd-4d51-90bd-38932fbfe127","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` is slow for incremental builds (2-4 seconds even with no changes), while Visual Studio rebuilds nearly instantly. They've verified:\n- No analyzers slowing things down\n- Incremental build targets are working\n- Project itself compiles in <500ms\n\nThe overhead is from MSBuild process startup and re-evaluation of the project graph on every CLI invocation.\n\nThe key insight here is that Visual Studio uses an MSBuild server (long-lived process) that keeps the project graph in memory, while `dotnet build` starts a fresh MSBuild process each time.\n\n\nThere are a few approaches to address this: `dotnet watch` keeps the build process alive between changes, `dotnet build-server` can manage long-lived MSBuild processes, and .NET 8+ supports enabling MSBuild Server mode through environment variables or project properties to avoid the startup overhead on each invocation. The key insight is that Visual Studio stays fast because it runs a persistent MSBuild process with the project system cached in memory, whereas `dotnet build` spawns a fresh process each time. Setting `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` replicates that behavior by maintaining a long-lived server, which combined with `dotnet watch build` for the development loop, should significantly reduce build times.","outputTokens":969},"id":"abcf3895-5109-4632-8dc1-a25e8aec7040","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:48:02.352Z","parentId":"91e5866f-ae8d-48e7-96f2-47daab79d1a7"}
